\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Top: beam transfer functions $B_\ell $ for all six ACT DR6 channels. The 90\,GHz beams (dashed lines) are broadest; the 220\,GHz beam (solid brown) is narrowest. Bottom: beam-shape systematic envelope $\Delta b_\ell /B_\ell $, showing the fractional beam uncertainty as a function of multipole. The horizontal dashed line marks the 1\% level. The pa4\_f220 envelope is approximately three times larger than the 90 and 150\,GHz envelopes.}}{8}{figure.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:beamenvelope}{{6}{8}{Top: beam transfer functions $B_\ell $ for all six ACT DR6 channels. The 90\,GHz beams (dashed lines) are broadest; the 220\,GHz beam (solid brown) is narrowest. Bottom: beam-shape systematic envelope $\Delta b_\ell /B_\ell $, showing the fractional beam uncertainty as a function of multipole. The horizontal dashed line marks the 1\% level. The pa4\_f220 envelope is approximately three times larger than the 90 and 150\,GHz envelopes}{figure.6}{}}
